@@dThornwood@@N

  A @@rnecrotic estate-forest@@N on the northern grave frontier beyond
Midgaard. Not merely haunted woods, not merely a fallen manor. The
defining trait is @@rassimilation@@N: manor and wilderness were metabolized
into one procedural ecology that treats death as input material.

  Four inseparable logics govern the estate. @@yManorial logic@@N persists
in iron gates bearing thorn motifs, hereditary titles, and protocols
of entry and exclusion. @@dFunerary logic@@N persists in barrows, charnel
verges, and exhumation cycles that process bone into infrastructure.
@@gForest logic@@N persists in root pressure, adaptive pathing, and canopy
suppression that responds to intrusion as a territorial organism. And
beneath all three lies @@esubstrate logic@@N -- a crystalline geological
formation predating human settlement, now the medium through which
the other three were fused into one operating system.

  Before noble walls stood here, ridge clans practiced face-down
oathbreaker burials and planted thorn rings as living containment.
The Harren family received the site by charter during Midgaard's
expansion, tasked with timber, hunting tithes, and burial lease fees.
What began as a working frontier property became a death-processing
facility as crisis years overwhelmed Midgaard's own burial grounds.

  The @@rRoot Covenant@@N emerged among grave laborers and bone-washers
who noticed the land responding to what was buried. Thorn rings grew
faster around certain graves. Root systems redirected after fresh
burials. Soil resisted exhumation in some plots and yielded readily
in others. They concluded that blood opens listening channels, roots
carry confession farther than bells, and bone remembers debt when
paper fails.

  Now @@dLord Harren@@N endures as an estate revenant preserving manorial
protocol, while the @@dThornwood Lich@@N maintains a biological binding
anchored in the crystal substrate. The @@rWild Hunt@@N -- the estate's
mobile enforcement arm -- patrols the perimeter, and its range has
extended farther toward the Lantern Road than in any prior generation.

  The binding is failing. Warden cartographers mark Thornwood with a
non-standard hazard sigil. Convoy writs treat its perimeter as a
legal exception: route promises remain valid around it, but never
through it. No warden patrol monitors the binding's status -- a gap
that may prove consequential as the failure accelerates.
